1
00:00:00,040 --> 00:00:02,633
Hey, my name is Maximilian Raff,

2
00:00:02,658 --> 00:00:04,443
and in my dissertation I developed

3
00:00:04,468 --> 00:00:07,147
mathematical tools to analyze and generate

4
00:00:07,172 --> 00:00:08,666
efficient periodic motions

5
00:00:08,691 --> 00:00:10,260
in robotic systems.

6
00:00:10,493 --> 00:00:12,168
When we build legged robots,

7
00:00:12,193 --> 00:00:13,400
we imagine them doing all kinds

8
00:00:13,425 --> 00:00:15,762
of repetitive tasks: moving objects,

9
00:00:15,787 --> 00:00:17,621
performing field operations,

10
00:00:17,646 --> 00:00:19,333
and navigating varied terrain

11
00:00:19,358 --> 00:00:20,468
at different speeds.

12
00:00:20,656 --> 00:00:22,025
So we need a library

13
00:00:22,050 --> 00:00:23,445
of repeatable motion patterns,

14
00:00:23,470 --> 00:00:26,434
or gaits, like walking or running.

15
00:00:26,680 --> 00:00:27,817
And because the robot

16
00:00:27,842 --> 00:00:29,863
runs on a single battery charge,

17
00:00:29,888 --> 00:00:32,368
these gaits must be energy-efficient.

18
00:00:32,769 --> 00:00:35,157
Finding these periodic gaits is challenging

19
00:00:35,182 --> 00:00:36,269
because the motion space

20
00:00:36,294 --> 00:00:38,092
is highly dynamic and nonlinear,

21
00:00:38,117 --> 00:00:39,504
while the actuation space

22
00:00:39,529 --> 00:00:41,479
is constrained by underactuation.

23
00:00:41,768 --> 00:00:43,228
A key idea in my work is

24
00:00:43,253 --> 00:00:45,073
to first study the robot's motions

25
00:00:45,098 --> 00:00:47,076
without actuation, setting the

26
00:00:47,101 --> 00:00:48,530
actuation input to zero

27
00:00:48,555 --> 00:00:50,581
and focusing purely on its natural,

28
00:00:50,606 --> 00:00:52,136
unforced dynamics.

29
00:00:52,414 --> 00:00:53,880
These natural dynamics also appear

30
00:00:53,905 --> 00:00:55,642
in passive dynamic walkers

31
00:00:55,667 --> 00:00:56,752
that move downhill

32
00:00:56,777 --> 00:00:58,408
powered only by gravity.

33
00:00:58,741 --> 00:01:00,602
This leads to the central question:

34
00:01:00,627 --> 00:01:01,858
can natural dynamics

35
00:01:01,883 --> 00:01:03,311
help us design and control

36
00:01:03,336 --> 00:01:05,326
energy-efficient legged systems?

37
00:01:05,637 --> 00:01:08,602
My dissertation contributes in three areas:

38
00:01:08,627 --> 00:01:10,864
systematically generating gait libraries

39
00:01:10,889 --> 00:01:12,777
using continuation methods,

40
00:01:12,802 --> 00:01:14,896
achieving energy efficient motion

41
00:01:14,921 --> 00:01:16,612
through optimal control,

42
00:01:16,837 --> 00:01:18,753
and leveraging natural dynamics

43
00:01:18,779 --> 00:01:21,034
from unactuated passive gaits,

44
00:01:21,330 --> 00:01:23,484
All centered around the idea

45
00:01:23,509 --> 00:01:25,037
that a robot's natural dynamics

46
00:01:25,062 --> 00:01:27,599
shape its energy-optimal gait libraries.

47
00:01:28,072 --> 00:01:29,367
Besides passive robots

48
00:01:29,392 --> 00:01:30,917
that use environmental energy

49
00:01:30,942 --> 00:01:32,582
to compensate losses from joint friction

50
00:01:32,607 --> 00:01:33,982
and foot impacts,

51
00:01:34,007 --> 00:01:36,058
there's also a fully lossless class

52
00:01:36,083 --> 00:01:38,734
of systems that conserve all their energy.

53
00:01:38,990 --> 00:01:40,176
They are theoretical,

54
00:01:40,201 --> 00:01:42,298
but incredibly useful for exploration

55
00:01:42,323 --> 00:01:43,696
because the periodic gaits

56
00:01:43,721 --> 00:01:44,965
can continuously morph

57
00:01:44,990 --> 00:01:46,283
from hopping in place

58
00:01:46,308 --> 00:01:48,063
to walking and running.

59
00:01:48,411 --> 00:01:50,856
Using a general mathematical abstraction

60
00:01:50,881 --> 00:01:52,363
based on hybrid dynamics,

61
00:01:52,388 --> 00:01:54,490
I proved that these periodic orbits

62
00:01:54,515 --> 00:01:56,062
are fundamentally connected.

63
00:01:56,314 --> 00:01:57,671
And with continuation methods

64
00:01:57,696 --> 00:01:59,375
I show how entire gait families

65
00:01:59,400 --> 00:02:01,560
can be systematically generated,

66
00:02:01,585 --> 00:02:02,770
starting from something

67
00:02:02,795 --> 00:02:04,834
as simple as standing still.

68
00:02:05,310 --> 00:02:06,984
But how do these passive gaits

69
00:02:07,009 --> 00:02:09,629
connect to generally actuated gaits?

70
00:02:09,940 --> 00:02:12,268
Well, since they use zero actuation,

71
00:02:12,293 --> 00:02:14,083
they don't draw any energy,

72
00:02:14,108 --> 00:02:15,800
That makes them globally optimal

73
00:02:15,825 --> 00:02:17,054
for a wide class

74
00:02:17,079 --> 00:02:19,114
of energetic cost functions.

75
00:02:19,520 --> 00:02:21,327
Using continuation methods again,

76
00:02:21,352 --> 00:02:23,530
paired with insight from optimization,

77
00:02:23,641 --> 00:02:26,071
I show how it's possible to systematically

78
00:02:26,096 --> 00:02:27,983
generate optimal gait libraries

79
00:02:28,008 --> 00:02:29,788
that originate from the two classes

80
00:02:29,813 --> 00:02:31,378
of passive dynamics,

81
00:02:31,490 --> 00:02:33,438
showcasing how this continuous path

82
00:02:33,463 --> 00:02:34,316
of optimal gaits can be followed

83
00:02:34,341 --> 00:02:36,811
in both simple

84
00:02:36,836 --> 00:02:39,969
and much more complex-legged systems.

85
00:02:40,403 --> 00:02:41,540
This approach reveals

86
00:02:41,565 --> 00:02:43,108
how a system's structure,

87
00:02:43,133 --> 00:02:44,629
like adding elastic springs,

88
00:02:44,679 --> 00:02:45,683
shapes energy use,

89
00:02:45,708 --> 00:02:47,475
and guides the joint optimization

90
00:02:47,500 --> 00:02:48,988
of hardware and control.

91
00:02:49,234 --> 00:02:50,674
Beyond legged robots,

92
00:02:50,699 --> 00:02:52,661
it can extend to exoskeletons

93
00:02:52,686 --> 00:02:53,801
and prostheses,

94
00:02:53,826 --> 00:02:55,463
offering a systematic way

95
00:02:55,488 --> 00:02:59,084
to connect design, control, and efficiency.

